Salem 1 Feby. 1781
Sir
Your esteemd favour of 27th ulto. came safe to hand. Inclosing the first of two Setts Bills Exchange upon Treasure at Paris for Eight thousand five hundred & Fifty Livres, the Small Balance is so Trifeling, that I beg you will not Trouble yourself to send strikethrough: (unclear) Consider your note as paid. I have Inclosed the Bills upon the note & consider it fully Paid, & will send it At the first opportunity, you will Please to Receive of Mrs. Clay the Money for the three Hhd. Rum which she sold us. I feal myself under particular obligatn. for your attention in sending me the Bills. I should be happy in keeping up a Correspondence with you & if I can be of any Service in Transacting Business here for you it will aford me Pleasure, our Friend unclear Clay has safe arivd. once more in the W. Indies I make no doubt he will make a good hand of it this winter, below you have price Curt. of W. Indies goods perhaps it may be of Some Advantage
I Am
Sir with Respect
yr. Most Obt. Sert.
Wm. Gray Jr

Boston Feby 8. 1781
Sir
Your favor of 3d Instant Inclosing a Bill of Exchange, have duly Reced &  Note ye Contents, I wrote you the 18th ulto. by post, the Receipt of wch you do not Acknowledge. The Bill you have sent me is so Large, that it will be difficult Selling it, at least it will not sell for so much a Smaller one.
I shall take care and Send or you a proper Voucher of the Sale of the Bill. I am entirely Satisfyed with the payment you have made. 
I Shall begin immediately to Send on the Rum & salt agreeable to your Request & if your money does not come in Season, shall do the best I can for your Interests
You mention only a part? of the Salt to be forwarded. I must request you to let me know by return of the post how much I shall Send on. If The weather holds Good, can have the whole delivered at Providence in 15 days. I know very well how those great Bodys Act when they have got a poor fellow to transact any Business for them If they get their ends answerd

answered, then the Devil take the hindmost
If you should have any other calls for any kind of Good from this Quarter, I always Stand to obay your Commands
I am in haste
Your most Obd Ser
Charles Miller

Boston March 1st 1781
Sir
Your favor of 14th Ult. came to (ie.,[uncertain]) by Post Last Evening— I have sold the Bill of Exchange at fifty three for one after much Difficulty had I been able to have kept it to this time, it would have sold for much more — Supposing from your letter 3rd. Ult.,that you wanted all your Rum & Salt Forwarded I have been pushing it with all Expedition, have only now about fifteen Loads Remaining on board, which will go on in a Day or Two — But I am much Disappointed in not Receiving a Remittance by this Opportunity as you wrote me in yours of 3rd. Ulto "that you expected in a few Days to be able to Remitt me Three or four hundred pounds, New Continental," on the strength of this I made no Doubt that I Should soon be repaid what Cash I Advanced — I must Therefore Beg you to use ye Utmost Endeavours to Remitt me by Return of Post, as I want Every Farthing of my own Money to purchase Bills, as they are about Rising fast
The

The French having Ten Millions of Livres Arrived in this Harbour, in hard Cash — As soon as I have compleated forwarding the Goods I Shall send you a particular Account of them — Pray push your great men for Cash — 
I am Sir
your Most Hbl. Sert.
Charles Miller

Bedford Dartmouth, 13th of 4 mt.? 1785
Respected Friends 
Whittelsey & Hubbard
By the Gottenburg Capt. Claghorn from Sweden, I have received acct Sales of some Tobacco which I ship'd by him and consign'd to my Friend Henry Greig of Gottenburg together with a parcel of 13 Casks of yours with 10 Casks of Parsons & Cooly of Springfield.   I have received acct. sales of mine & yours & yours I inclose with that of Parsons & Cooly - together with your acct. with me on that Adventure - which was cosign'd to me with mine - it is a poor price for Tobacco in Europe, but New England Tobacco even of the best quality will not answer at that market, indeed nothing short of best kind of Virginia - and my friend writes me he was very sorry it was so poor - , By your acct you will see what I have for you , and strikethrough: which I request your directions therein of which I must do with your Good, by first opportunity, as also directions from Parsons & Cooly, who I beg you will inform hereof - in the mean while remain

East Windsor May 8th 1781
Sir
I have lately received a letter from you which acquaints me that you have converced with W. Hubbard and other gentlemen concerning the Hatts which I sent you I am very Sorry that they did not answer your expectation, was I it in my power as it is strikethrough: most agreeable to you I should pay you to the valley? of what I received for the hatts, but as I have bin building what money I had is spent that way and therefore I must do as I can, I request you to except of all of these but those made of the coarse wool, which I think you agreed to when I was at your store as to those of the coarse kind I leave it with your generosity to do the best you can with them, as to the strikethrough: (unclear) of the trimmings they are none others than the same kind of which you have ever had of me when there was no fault found with them I think it harde or me to deduct one quarter from the value of these to have them pass but necessity obliges me to leave them because I am not able to redeem them, I intend the others shall answer your expectation I did never intend the unclear should suffer by me but was deceived by my workemen as I have told you before neither do I yet mean that they shall if it is in my power consistent with reason to satisfy them. 
I am your Humble Servant
Noah Welles

Jabez Hamlin Esq Judge of the Court of Probate for the District of Middletown in the State of Connecticutt in New England holding said Court to Deacn. Chauncey Whittelsey of said Middletown. Greeting -- whereas the Country Court in and for the County of Hartford on the First Tuesday of Feby last did sentence judge and Decree the Estate Real & Personal of James Jauncey Esq of New York Lying and Being in the State of Connecticutt to be forfeit to & for the use of said State of Connecticutt and to be used and administered on according to one Certain Statute of said State Entitled an Act for Confiscating the Estates of Persons Inimical to the Independence and Liberties of the united States within this State and for payment of their debts and Divesting Proceeding therein and being Desirous that said estate both Real & Personal should be administered Accrdg to Law. 
I do therefore Trusting in your Fidelity & Care Commit unto you the said Chauncey Whittelsey full Power of Administration the Goods, Chattels, Credits & Estate of the said James Jauncey Esq According to Law. and to pay all Debts, in which he stood Bound in this State so far as his Good, Chattels & Estate can Extend according to the Value thereof and to make a true & perfect Inventory of all and Singular Goods, Chattels, Credits and Estate of the said James Jauncey, and Exhibit the Same into the Registry of the said Court of Probate within Twenty Days, after the date hereof and also render to the said Court a true & Plain Acct. of your administration within One Year from the Date hereof and I do by these presents ordain depute & constitute you Administrator of all and Singular the Goods, Chattels & Estate aforesaid, In Witness whereof I have Caused the Clerk of sd. Court to Sign these presents and fix the seal of said office thereto this 7th day of May ADom 1785
Sign'd pr Order.

New London Octo 2 1781
Dear Sir,
Twice I attempted to come and Settle the Hunters Accots, the first time I carryd. the accots. to Midddletown in order for Settlements, but was obliged to return immediately back on acct. of some Business that was urgent; occasiond by the fire
The next time meeting Mr. Hallam on the Road of East Haddam, was obliged to return- as I am extremely anxious to have the Accots. Instantly closed, being exceedingly in want of all the cash that may be due us, must beg the particular favour of you (as my Brother is Sick & it will be very inconvenient for me to leave home) - if you will assist my Brother George in adjusting the Accots. with Mr. Merrills; shall most willingly make you any satisfaction for the time & trouble - our disagreable Situation at this place makes it more necessary to close all out Accots. - if any

Ballance should be due from yourself you will take care to stop a full suffiency for out fitts of Brign. three sisters - please to Acquaint Mr. Merrills of the Day you will attend on it, & after Settlement be kind enough to acquaint my Brother who to call on (if any) for some Cash - could you Assist him in Jogging them to pay me you would exceedingly oblige me
hope it will not be inconvenient for you to Attend on this Matter; were it not for our present Situation would not give you the Trouble - shall strikethrough: most a? most chearfully make you any allowance for your trouble & kind assistance
I am Sir with respect & Esteem
your Hbl Servt
Edward Hallam
Chauncy Whittlesey Esq

At a general Assembly of the State of Connecticut, holden at Newhaven on the 2d. Thursday of October, Anno Dom. 1790
Upon the Petition of Theophilus Merriman of Wallingford in the County of New Haven shewing to this Assembly that in the year AD 1771 he the said Merriman purchased of James Jauncey of the City & County of New York his the said Jaunceys part & proportion in seventy Acres of Land & a Dwelling House, sutuate in said Wallingford, being Lands which David Cook by Deed dated January 14th AD 1763 conveyed to said Jauncey & John Smith, together with said Jaunceys right & Interests in certain Lands, sutuate in said Wallingford on the North Side of the Country road, which said Cook purchased of Nathaniel Curtiss & Stephen Peck & by said Deed conveyed to said Smith and Jauncey, and that he the said Merriman has received no Deed of said Lands from said Jauncey & that said Jaunceys estate hath since been confiscated to & for the use of this State, praying? that some suitable may be authorised to remain & release? & quit claim to said Petitioner his Heirs & Assigns, all right tittle Interest & estate which this State derived & acquired in & upon said described Lands by virtue of said Jaunceys estates being confiscated as aforesaid as by Petition on file.
Resolved by this Assembly that Chauncey Whittlesey of Middletown in Middlesex County late Administrator on the confiscated estate of said Jauncey be & he is hereby authorised & impowered in behalf of this State to make, execute & acknowledge a Deed of said Lands to said Theophilus his Heirs & Assigns, therein & thereby remising, releasing and quitclaiming to said Theophilus his Heirs & Assigns all right & tittle Interest & estate, which this State, derived & acquired in & upon said described Lands by virtue of said Confiscation of said Jaunceys estate as aforesaid.
A true Copy of Record
